AGI -&nbsp;Conferred by the mayor of Rome, Roberto Gualtieri, the Lupa Capitolina to the Norwegian writer Jon Fosse, Nobel Prize 2023 for Literature >. The ceremony of the most important recognition of the City of Rome took place in the Flag Hall, in Capitol, where the Norwegian writer signed the Capitoline Golden Book. Previously, a private interview was held between mayor and writer, which was also the Councillor for Culture of Rome Capital, Massimiliano Smeriglio.
In his speech Gualtieri spoke of "great honor" having Jon Fosse in Rome, in Capitol, and this recognition "want to express gratitude for his works, his art, his poems. And in a time of gloom, dominated by technological speed, for us readers - Gualtieri has added - his books are a place of refreshment, meditation, knowledge, to resume dialogue with ourselves and is also a great message of hope in a year of Jubilee that Pope Francis wanted to indicate precisely in the sign of hope". Gualtieri took the opportunity to formulate his wishes to the Pope and those of the city of Rome. &nbsp;
The mayor then added that "in this city he could not find listening and echoes a voice like that of Jon Fosse. Rome is also a city of spirit, literary, place of culture, faith, imagination where poetry and art find abode. Thank you for accepting the invitation to participate this evening at the Literature Festival, scheduled at 21 at the Auditorium of the Parco della Musica. Rome was among the first European cities to stage the theatrical works of Fosse. There is a strong common element: Rome is also the global center of Catholicism, and among the pages of Fosse passes this thought. We are a community sensitive to the spiritual dimension and - addressing the writer - in his works emanates a humanism full of wisdom > and a strong sense of hope. And Rome will continue to listen to his voice."
Born in Strandebarm in 1959, Fosse is a writer and playwright and is universally considered one of the most important contemporary authors. He currently lives in Grotten's honorary residence in Oslo, granted by the King for his literary merits. This evening's event, open to the public and free of charge, will see Fosse dialogue with writer Claudia Durastanti and translator Andrea Romanzi. It will be the first of the previews of Literature, International Festival of Rome, historical literary event promoted by the Assessorato alla Cultura di Roma Capitale. &nbsp;

