AGI - Black Day for Work: Three fatal accidents have occurred in the last hours in three separate episodes. The victims are three workers, a 51-year-old deceased a&nbsp;Sant'Antonio Abate, in the Neapolitan &nbsp; and a 22-year-old who lost his life in Pordenone in Friuli Venezia Giulia, finally, a 38-year-old was invested and killed on the A1 near Orvieto.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
In the first case, the worker was stuck in the conveyor belt in the company &nbsp; disposal of the Neapolitan waste where he worked.
The second episode occurred in the Stm factory of Molino di Campagna, in the province of Pordenone. The company specializes in hot steel processing. According to an initial reconstruction of the polluters, the 22-year-old worker would have been hit in the back by a metal fragment while working near a mold that would explode causing him very serious internal injuries.
Upon arrival of the medical staff alerted by colleagues working with automedical and ambulance the young man was found under cardiac arrest. The prolonged maneuvers of reanimation were unfortunately vain, man died.&nbsp;
Finally, a 38-year-old worker died invested by a tir while working on the North A1 road near Orvieto. According to the online media, man would be dependent on a company responsible for carrying out maintenance operations on the highway.
<h2>Cgil, slaughter does not stop with bureaucracy
“Three workers of 22, 38 and 50 years are the last victims of an endless slaughter at work. These tragedies, which sink their causes into saving at any cost, in rush, in the lack of investments and controls, cannot be stopped with more or less bureaucratic interventions.” Thus, in a note, the confederal secretary of the Cgil, Francesca Re David, > about the three fatal accidents of the last hours, in the province of Naples, Pordenone and Terni.
For the union leader “the devaluation of workers and workers is the true responsible of these deaths and no general appeal to the culture of security can be effective without a culture of the centrality of the person on profit”.
"With the Labor Referendums of 8 and 9 June, promoted by the Cgil, we want to reverse this logic by intervening on the responsibilities in the chain of contracts and precariousness. Without this paradigm shift - King David concludes - the massacre will not stop."
&nbsp;
